{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473807","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473807"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:14:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:14:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11361"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11361","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11361"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.04,0.03,0.01,0.74]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4006"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107723"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4006","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4006"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11361"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90155"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"3406"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"},{"type":"tags","id":"9616"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"12901"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4243"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4285"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7322"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7639"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9529"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35115"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44099"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107723","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107723"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA five-day-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with her mother for a routine check-up. She was born at 39 weeks gestation to a primigravida woman. The mother had gestational diabetes controlled with insulin during pregnancy. The delivery was assisted with forceps, and the birth weight was 4310 g. The baby was noticed to have yellowing of her upper body during her check at 48 hours old. She currently weighs 4100 g. She is exclusively breastfed every three hours and has four wet nappies a day. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her vital signs are within normal limits. There is jaundice to the nipple line and dry mucous membranes. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaemoglobin, sodium, and liver function tests are within normal ranges\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EBilirubin: Conjugated 16 \u00b5mol/L, Unconjugated 210 \u00b5mol/L\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EMaternal blood group A, Rh-positive\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFetal blood group O, Rh-positive\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe bilirubin level is plotted on an age-appropriate chart and is found to be below the treatment line.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate course of action?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Commence top-up bottle feeds along with breastfeeding","Abdominal ultrasound","Intravenous fluid therapy","Strict fluid monitoring and indwelling catheter insertion","Ongoing support, and breastfeeding education"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis baby is presenting with symptoms of jaundice, however the bilirubin level is below the phototherapy line and the baby has only lost 5% of weight from birth weight (up to 10-12% of birth weight is expected to be lost in the first few days of life, and is within normal parameters). Physiological jaundice is a common finding in the first week of life, resulting from increased breakdown of fetal haemoglobin and immature hepatic conjugation pathways. Breastfeeding jaundice, a subset of physiological jaundice, occurs when there is insufficient caloric intake in the first days of life, often due to delayed onset of mature milk production. Regular, effective breastfeeding is crucial to stimulate maternal milk supply and promote bilirubin excretion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven this, \u003Cstrong\u003Eongoing support, and breastfeeding education\u003C/strong\u003E around continued breast feeds is recommended. This includes encouraging frequent breastfeeding, monitoring for adequate wet nappies, and arranging close follow-up to ensure continued weight gain and resolution of jaundice. Additionally, provision of lactation support to optimise latch, positioning and efficient milk transfer may be needed for some mum-baby dyads, and can be provided by a lactation consultant or medical practitioner with interest and experience in the field.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing top-up bottle feeds\u003C/strong\u003E along with breastfeeding would be indicated if there was greater than 10% weight loss from birth weight, and/or with associated jaundice requiring phototherapy treatment. Introducing supplementary feeds in infants with bilirubin below the treatment line can be counterproductive, as it may reduce the frequency and effectiveness of breastfeeding, thereby impairing maternal milk supply and prolonging jaundice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E would be used to rule out biliary atresia, a serious life-threatening condition, if neonatal jaundice persists for more than two weeks or if there is a significant elevation in conjugated bilirubin. This newborn is only five days old and has a low conjugated bilirubin, making this investigation unnecessary at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous fluid therapy\u003C/strong\u003E can be appropriate for the treatment of jaundice secondary to inadequate feeding or dehydration in neonates, but is typically reserved for cases of severe dehydration. This baby is mildly dehydrated at most, and oral rehydration with breastmilk is preferred.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStrict fluid monitoring and indwelling catheter insertion\u003C/strong\u003E may be appropriate in the case of an acutely unwell child with severe dehydration or when precise measurement of urine output is required. In this well-appearing newborn, daily weights and monitoring of wet nappies are sufficient for tracking fluid status.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, this case presents a newborn with mild jaundice and minimal weight loss. The most appropriate management is to provide ongoing support, reassurance, and education to the mother about breastfeeding. This approach encourages continued breastfeeding, which will likely resolve the mild jaundice as the baby\u0027s caloric intake increases. Close follow-up should be arranged to monitor the baby\u0027s weight and jaundice levels.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Physiological jaundice is common in the first week of life and usually resolves with regular, effective breastfeeding.","Supplementary feeding in infants with bilirubin below the treatment line can impair maternal milk supply and is generally not recommended.","Ongoing support, reassurance, and education are key in managing mild neonatal jaundice with adequate weight and feeding."],"references":["Leung AK, Sauve RS. Breastfeeding and breast milk jaundice. Journal of the Royal Society of Health. 1989 Dec;109(6):213-7. Available at: https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/146642408910900615","BMJ Best Practice. Biliary atresia [Internet]. BMJ; 2020 [Updated 2020; cited 2021 Sep 27]. Available from: https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/739","Wong RJ, Bhutani Vk. Unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia in the newborn: Pathogenesis and etiology. In: Uptodate [online]. 2019 [Updated 2019; cited 2021 Sep 27]. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/etiology-and-pathogenesis-of-neonatal-unconjugated-hyperbilirubinemia","The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Jaundice in early infancy [online]. RCH; 2020 [Updated 2020; cited 2021 Sep 27]. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Jaundice_in_early_infancy/","The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Dehydration [online]. RCH; 2022 [Updated 2020; cited 2022 Oct 23]. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Dehydration/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90155"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11361"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90155"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-02T10:52:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-02T10:52:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4006"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107723"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"me